</li><li id="tree_64157207" class="comment oneline"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64157207" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64157207" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64157207" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64157207" name="comment_link_64157207" href="//yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23192425&amp;cid=64157207" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64157207)" >Trivial to reverse the burden of proof</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64157207" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64157207); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~misnohmer">misnohmer</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~misnohmer">( 1636461 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64157207"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64157207">Run the following code on a computer:<br>
<tt>
  print "The other computer is unreliable"
</tt> <br>
Now the burden of proof is on the alleged unreliable computer's operator or creator to prove that it is in fact reliable, since the computer running the code above is presumed correct unless proven otherwise (which would require proving the alleged unreliable computer is in fact reliable). If you remove the presumption that computers are always correct, then again, a proof is required to show the computer reliability.</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64157207">

</div>
</div>

<div id="replyto_64157207"></div>

